Maharshi Dayanand Saraswati — Views on God, the Vedas, and Idol Worship

1. His View of God
Dayanand taught that God is:
One and only one.
Formless (Nirakar).
Omniscient (knows everything).
Omnipresent (present everywhere).
Eternal and unborn.
Just and merciful.
He believed God cannot be born as a human, animal, or any physical form because an infinite being cannot be limited by a body.
The sacred syllable "Om" was regarded as the highest name of God.


2. His View of the Vedas
Dayanand considered the four Vedas:
Rigveda
Yajurveda
Samaveda
Atharvaveda
to be the oldest and most authoritative scriptures.
He taught that:
The Vedas were revealed by God at the beginning of creation.
They contain spiritual, moral, and practical knowledge.
Any belief or practice should be tested against the Vedas.
Because of this, Arya Samaj often uses the slogan "Back to the Vedas."


3. His View of Idol Worship
This was one of his most controversial teachings.
Dayanand argued:
Stone, metal, wood, or clay images are man-made.
God is not contained inside an object.
Worship should be directed to God Himself, not to a representation.
He believed prayer, meditation, Vedic study, and yajna/havan were proper forms of worship.
Many other Hindu traditions disagree and see murtis as aids to devotion rather than as ordinary objects. This is one of the biggest differences between Arya Samaj and many other Hindu schools.


4. His View of Caste
Dayanand taught that:
A person's status should be based on qualities, education, and actions.
Birth alone should not determine social rank.
He interpreted the ancient varna system as merit-based rather than hereditary.


5. His View on Social Reform
He supported:
Education for women.
Widow remarriage.
Opposition to child marriage.
Universal education.
Social uplift and moral reform.
These ideas made Arya Samaj influential in modern India.
